        section
          h3 What's going on here?

          ol
            li P(E|C) &cong; 0.5 > P(E|&not;C) &cong; 0.4
            li P(E|C,F) &cong; 0.2 < P(E|&not;C,F) &cong; 0.3
            li P(E|C,&not;F) &cong; 0.6 < P(E|&not;C,&not;F) &cong; 0.7

          p where C - treatment (cause), E - recovery (effect), F - female (feature)

        section
          h3 Should we treat a patient with the drug?

          p.fragment If we don't know their gender...
            span.fragment.indent Yes! P(E|C) > P(E|&not;C)

          p.fragment If they're female...
            span.fragment.indent No! P(E|C,F) < P(E|&not;C,F)

          p.fragment If they're male...
            span.fragment.indent No! P(E|C,&not;F) < P(E|&not;C,&not;F)

          img.fragment(src="img/lol-srsly.jpg")

        section
          h3 Pearl: Probability calculus isn't enough

          blockquote.full-width.
            The explanation for Simpson's paradox should be clear to readers of this book, since we have taken great
            care in distinguishing <i>seeing</i> from <i>doing</i>. The conditioning operator in probability calculus
            stands for the evidential conditional "given that we see," whereas the do() operator was devised to
            represent the causal conditional "given that we do." Accordingly, the inequality P(E|C) > P(E|&not;C) is
            not a statement about C being a positive causal factor for E, properly written P(E|do(C)) > P(E|do(&not;C)),
            but rather about C being positive evidence for E, which may be due to spurious confounding factors that
            cause both C and E.

        section
          h3 Causal assumptions are essential

          p.fragment(data-fragment-index=0) <b>Key assumption:</b> Males tend to use the drug more (F &rarr; C)
          p.indent.fragment(data-fragment-index=0).
            Condition on the confounding variable F: Follow the gender-specific measures and never prescribe C

          p.fragment(data-fragment-index=1).
            <b>Different scenario:</b> F is high blood pressure, and the drug may raise blood pressure (C &rarr; F)
          p.indent.fragment(data-fragment-index=1).
            No point conditioning on F: Follow the overall measures and always prescribe C

          img.fragment(data-fragment-index=1, src="img/simpsons-paradox-causal-assumptions.png")

        section
          h3 One last scenario

          p.fragment(data-fragment-index=0).
            F is brown eye colour, and we can't assume it affects drug selection, or is affected by it
          p.indent.fragment(data-fragment-index=0).
            No point conditioning on F: Follow the overall measures and always prescribe C

          p.fragment(data-fragment-index=1).
            <b>Generally:</b> The decision whether to use F to predict E can't only depend on the data &ndash; the data
            may lie

